title: Your Thursday Briefing: Russia Declares Martial Law In Occupied Ukraine
description: Plus the British prime minister pushed to resign, China’s most powerful female politician to retire.

title: Biden Expands Effort to Lower Gas Prices and Secure Energy Independence
description: Draining of emergency oil reserves draws criticism that the White House is trying to lower gas prices with midterm election politics in mind.

title: Schoolgirl’s Killing Shocks France and Fuels Right-Wing Fury
description: An Algerian woman who had been ordered to leave the country has been arrested and charged in the killing of a girl who was found in a box in Paris, stoking anger over the government’s immigration record.

title: Russia Shrinks Forces in Syria, a Factor in Israeli Strategy There
description: Moscow withdrew a key air defense system and some troops to bolster its war in Ukraine, officials said, potentially altering Israel’s calculations about striking Syria or arming Ukraine.

title: Liz Truss or Lettuce: Who Will Wilt First?
description: Inspired by a columnist’s turn of phrase, a British newspaper is tracking whether the embattled prime minister can outlast off-the-shelf produce.

title: In Britain, Demands for Tough Response After Beating at Chinese Consulate
description: Activists who fled Hong Kong and some British lawmakers have called for a tough government response to the episode in Manchester, as the man who was beaten spoke out.

title: Preserving a Palestinian Identity in the Kitchen
description: With many Palestinians fearful that their cuisine is being lost, kitchen practices handed down by family matriarchs for generations are still being passed along.

title: Liz Truss, Jeered in UK Parliament, Insists She Can Govern
description: Prime Minister Liz Truss of Britain, who has seen her entire economic agenda repudiated, told lawmakers that she was not a quitter.

title: Iranian Climber Elnaz Rekabi Is Welcomed by Crowds in Tehran
description: Elnaz Rekabi, whose appearance without a head scarf at an event in Seoul raised fears about her future, was welcomed home by crowds in Tehran. Her motivations, and her fate, however, remain unclear.

title: The Two Inflation Crises
description: Why Europe’s inflation crisis is different from America’s.

title: Russian Proxies Vow to Relocate Civilians as Ukrainian Forces Press Toward Southern City
description: Pro-Kremlin officials in Kherson said they would move tens of thousands of people, as the commander of Russia’s invasion acknowledged his army’s grip on the city was tenuous.

title: Bread Prices Skyrocket as Inflation Grips Europe
description: The elevated costs of flour, nuts, eggs and even electricity are forcing bakers to increase their prices and cut their production.

title: India Bars Kashmiri Photographer From Traveling to Receive Pulitzer
description: The Indian authorities stopped Sanna Irshad Mattoo at the New Delhi airport, in the latest case of harassment of journalists in the country.

title: For Women in China’s Communist Party, It’s Lonely at the Top
description: Mao’s phrase that “women hold up half the sky,” rings hollow as China’s most powerful female politician readies for retirement with few others in line.

title: Germany Sacks Cybersecurity Official Over Possible Links to Russia
description: The move comes after reports that the official kept contact with a lobbying group that had links to Russian intelligence even after Russia invaded Ukraine.

title: South Korean Super App Kakao Goes Down, Putting a Halt on Life
description: A days-long outage at Kakao has led to the resignation of a co-CEO and a reckoning over Big Tech’s extensive grip over the South Korean economy.

title: Russian officials hint that their hold on Kherson is shaky.
Waiting for Refugee Status, Thousands Live in Limbo
description: As the Biden administration prioritizes resettling people fleeing Ukraine and Afghanistan, many other refugees are waiting years in a system struggling to rebuild.

title: Britain Scales Back Foreign Aid, Threatening Progress in Global Health
description: The nation is often the second-largest donor to groups working in poor countries to prevent and treat infectious diseases, and to provide reproductive health services to women.

title: South Korea Gets Squeezed Between the US and China
description: The intensifying rivalry between Washington and Beijing is causing jitters in South Korea, where security ties and economic priorities are not always aligned.

title: Your Wednesday Briefing
description: Russian attacks on Ukrainian power stations.

title: Where Have All the Men in Moscow Gone?
description: Across the capital, there are noticeably fewer men at restaurants, stores and social gatherings. Many have been called up to fight in Ukraine. Others have fled to avoid being drafted.
